LinkedList in Java

LinkedList is a class in Java that implements the List interface.

It stores elements using a linked structure, not an array like ArrayList.

Each element (node) contains:

the data
a reference to the next element
(and to the previous element)
How it works (simple idea)

In LinkedList, elements are not stored next to each other in memory.

Instead, each element points to the next one:

[Apple] -> [Banana] -> [Orange]
Why use LinkedList?

Use LinkedList when:

you часто добавляешь или удаляешь элементы
работаешь с началом или концом списка
Creating LinkedList
import java.util.LinkedList;
import java.util.List;

List<String> list = new LinkedList<>();
Common Methods
Adding elements
list.add("Apple");        // add to end
list.addFirst("Banana");  // add to beginning
list.addLast("Orange");   // add to end
Accessing elements
list.get(0);        // by index
list.getFirst();    // first element
list.getLast();     // last element
Removing elements
list.remove(0);         // by index
list.removeFirst();     // first element
list.removeLast();      // last element
Important Features
maintains order
allows duplicates
allows null
implements both List and Deque
Performance (very important)
Operation	LinkedList
get(index)	slow (O(n))
add/remove (start/end)	fast (O(1))
add/remove (middle)	faster than ArrayList
When NOT to use LinkedList

Do NOT use it when:

you часто обращаешься по индексу (get(i))
тебе нужен быстрый доступ к элементам
LinkedList vs ArrayList (short)
ArrayList → fast reading
LinkedList → fast insert/remove
Summary
LinkedList uses nodes instead of array
good for frequent insert/remove
slow for index access
best for working with beginning/end of list
